# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ntp-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] In serial communication, clock synchronization can refer to clock recovery, which achieves frequency synchronization, as opposed to full phase synchronization.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Such clock synchronization is used in synchronization in telecommunications and automatic baud rate detection.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Plesiochronous or isochronous operation refers to a system with frequency synchronization and loose constraints on phase synchronization.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Synchronous operation implies a tighter synchronization based on time perhaps in addition to frequency.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] As a result of the difficulties managing time at smaller scales, there are problems associated with clock skew that take on more complexity in distributed computing in which several computers will need to realize the same global time.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] For instance, in Unix systems, the *make* command is used to compile new or modified code and seeks to avoid recompiling unchanged code.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The *make* command uses the clock of the machine it runs on to determine which source files need to be recompiled.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] If the sources reside on a separate file server and the two machines have unsynchronized clocks, the *make* program might not produce the correct results.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is required for accurate reproduction of streaming media.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Clock synchronization is a significant component of audio over Ethernet systems.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] In a system with a central server, the synchronization solution is trivial; the server will dictate the system time.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm and the Berkeley algorithm are potential solutions to the clock synchronization problem in this environment.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] In distributed computing, the problem takes on more complexity because a global time is not easily known.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The most used clock synchronization solution on the Internet is the Network Time Protocol (NTP), which is a layered client-server architecture based on User Datagram Protocol (UDP) message passing.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Lamport timestamps and vector clocks are concepts of the logical clock in distributed computing.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] In a wireless network, the problem becomes even more challenging due to the possibility of collision of the synchronization packets on the wireless medium and the higher drift rate of clocks on low-cost wireless devices.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The Berkeley algorithm is suitable for systems where a radio clock is not present.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] This system has no way of making sure of the actual time other than by maintaining a global average time as the global time.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] A time server will periodically fetch the time from all the time clients, average the results, and then report back to the clients the adjustment that needs be made to their local clocks to achieve the average.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] This algorithm highlights the fact that internal clocks may vary not only in the time they contain but also in the clock rate.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Clock-sampling mutual network synchronization (CS-MNS) is suitable for distributed and mobile applications.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] It has been shown to be scalable over mesh networks that include indirectly-linked non-adjacent nodes and is compatible with IEEE 802.11 and similar standards.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] It can be accurate to the order of a few microseconds but requires direct physical wireless connectivity with negligible link delay (less than 1 microsecond) on links between adjacent nodes, limiting the distance between neighboring nodes to a few hundred meters.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm relies on the existence of a time server.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The time server maintains its clock by using a radio clock or other accurate time source, then all other computers in the system stay synchronized with it.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] A time client will maintain its clock by making a procedure call to the time server.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Variations of this algorithm make more precise time calculations by factoring in network radio propagation time.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] In addition to its use in navigation, the Global Positioning System (GPS) can also be used for clock synchronization.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The accuracy of GPS time signals is ±10 nanoseconds.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Using GPS (or other satellite navigation systems) for synchronization requires a receiver connected to an antenna with unobstructed view of the sky.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] IRIG timecodes are standard formats for transferring timing information.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Atomic frequency standards and GPS receivers designed for precision timing are often equipped with an IRIG output.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The standards were created by the Telecommunications Working Group of the United States military's Inter-Range Instrumentation Group (IRIG), the standards body of the Range Commanders Council.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Work on these standards started in October 1956, and the original standards were accepted in 1960.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Network Time Protocol (NTP) is a highly robust protocol, widely deployed throughout the Internet.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Well tested over the years, it is generally regarded as the state of the art in distributed time synchronization protocols for unreliable networks.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] It can reduce synchronization offsets to times of the order of a few milliseconds over the public Internet and to sub-millisecond levels over local area networks.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] A simplified version of the NTP protocol, Simple Network Time Protocol (SNTP), can also be used as a pure single-shot stateless primary/secondary synchronization protocol, but lacks the sophisticated features of NTP, and thus has much lower performance and reliability levels.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Precision Time Protocol (PTP) is a master/slave protocol for delivery of highly accurate time over local area networks.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Time Synchronization (RBS) algorithm is often used in wireless networks and sensor networks.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] In this scheme, an initiator broadcasts a reference message to urge the receivers to adjust their clocks.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Infrastructure Synchronization (RBIS) protocol is a master/slave synchronization protocol, like RBS, based on a receiver/receiver synchronization paradigm.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] It is specifically tailored to be used in IEEE 802.11 wireless networks configured in infrastructure mode (i.e., coordinated by an access point).
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The protocol does not require any modification to the access point.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Synchronous Ethernet uses Ethernet in a synchronous manner such that when combined with synchronization protocols such as PTP in the case of the White Rabbit Project, sub-nanosecond synchronization accuracy is achieved.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is achieved in wireless ad hoc networks through sending synchronization messages in a multi-hop manner and each node progressively synchronizing with the node that is the immediate sender of a synchronization message.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Examples include Flooding Time Synchronization Protocol (FTSP), and Harmonia, both able to achieve synchronization with accuracy on the order of microseconds.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Researchers from Stanford and Google introduced Huygens, a probe-based, end-to-end clock synchronization algorithm.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] Huygens is implemented in software and thus can be deployed in data centers or in public cloud environments.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] By leveraging some key aspects of modern data centers and applying novel estimation algorithms and signal processing techniques, the Huygens algorithm achieved an accuracy of tens of nanoseconds even at high network load.
[src:ntp-protocol/clock-synchronization] The findings of this research are being tested in financial market applications.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The **Network Time Protocol** (**NTP**) is a networking protocol for clock synchronization between computer systems over packet-switched, variable-latency data networks.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In operation since before 1985, NTP is one of the oldest Internet protocols in current use.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP is intended to synchronize participating computers to within a few milliseconds of Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It uses the intersection algorithm, a modified version of Marzullo's algorithm, to select accurate time servers and is designed to mitigate the effects of variable network latency.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP can usually maintain time to within tens of milliseconds over the public Internet, and can achieve better than one millisecond accuracy in local area networks under ideal conditions.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Asymmetric routes and network congestion can cause errors of 100 ms or more.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The protocol is usually described in terms of a client–server model, but can as easily be used in peer-to-peer relationships where both peers consider the other to be a potential time source.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Implementations send and receive timestamps using the User Datagram Protocol (UDP); the service is normally on port number 123, and in some modes both sides use this port number.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] They can also use broadcasting or multicasting, where clients passively listen to time updates after an initial round-trip calibrating exchange.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP supplies a warning of any impending leap second adjustment, but no information about local time zones or daylight saving time is transmitted.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The current protocol is version 4 (NTPv4), which is backward compatible with version 3.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A typical NTP client regularly polls one or more NTP servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The client must compute its time offset and round-trip delay.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Time offset *θ* is the positive or negative (client time > server time) difference in absolute time between the two clocks.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] To derive the expression for the offset, note that for the request packet, $t_{0}+\theta +\delta /2=t_{1}$ and for the response packet, $t_{3}+\theta -\delta /2=t_{2}$ Solving for *θ* yields the definition of the time offset.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The values for *θ* and *δ* are passed through filters and subjected to statistical analysis ("mitigation").
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Outliers are discarded and an estimate of time offset is derived from the best three remaining candidates.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The clock frequency is then adjusted to reduce the offset gradually ("discipline"), creating a feedback loop.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Accurate synchronization is achieved when both the incoming and outgoing routes between the client and the server have symmetrical nominal delay.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] If the routes do not have a common nominal delay, a systematic bias exists of half the difference between the forward and backward travel times.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A number of approaches have been proposed to measure asymmetry, but among practical implementations only chrony seems to have one included.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1979, network time synchronization technology was used in what was possibly the first public demonstration of Internet services running over a trans-Atlantic satellite network, at the National Computer Conference in New York.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The technology was later described in the 1981 Internet Engineering Note (IEN) 173 and a public protocol was developed from it that was documented in RFC 778.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The technology was first deployed in a local area network as part of the Hello routing protocol and implemented in the Fuzzball router, an experimental operating system used in network prototyping, where it ran for many years.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Other related network tools were available both then and now.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] They include the Daytime and Time protocols for recording the time of events, as well as the ICMP Timestamp messages and IP Timestamp option (RFC 781).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1985, NTP version 0 (NTPv0) was implemented in both Fuzzball and Unix, and the NTP packet header and round-trip delay and offset calculations, which have persisted into NTPv4, were documented in RFC 958.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Despite the relatively slow computers and networks available at the time, accuracy of better than 100 milliseconds was usually obtained on Atlantic spanning links, with accuracy of tens of milliseconds on Ethernet networks.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1988, a much more complete specification of the NTPv1 protocol, with associated algorithms, was published in RFC 1059.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It drew on the experimental results and clock filter algorithm documented in RFC 956 and was the first version to describe the client–server and peer-to-peer modes.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1991, the NTPv1 architecture, protocol and algorithms were brought to the attention of a wider engineering community with the publication of an article by David L.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Mills in the *IEEE Transactions on Communications*.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1989, RFC 1119 was published defining NTPv2 by means of a state machine, with pseudocode to describe its operation.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It introduced a management protocol and cryptographic authentication scheme which have both survived into NTPv4, along with the bulk of the algorithm.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] However the design of NTPv2 was criticized for lacking formal correctness by the DTSS community, and the clock selection procedure was modified to incorporate Marzullo's algorithm for NTPv3 onwards.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The RFC included an analysis of all sources of error, from the reference clock down to the final client, which enabled the calculation of a metric that helps choose the best server where several candidates appear to disagree.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In subsequent years, as new features were added and algorithm improvements were made, it became apparent that a new protocol version was required.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 2010, RFC 5905 was published containing a proposed specification for NTPv4.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Following the retirement of Mills from the University of Delaware, the reference implementation is currently maintained as an open source project led by Harlan Stenn.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] On the IANA side, a ntp (network time *protocols*) work group is in charge of reviewing proposed drafts.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The protocol has significantly progressed since NTPv4.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] As of 2022, three RFC documents describing updates to the protocol have been published, not counting the numerous peripheral standards such as Network Time Security.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Mills had mentioned plans for a "NTPv5" on his page, but one was never published.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Lichvar of chrony was initiated in 2020 and includes security, accuracy, and scaling changes.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] As NTP replaced the old Time Protocol, some use cases nevertheless found the full protocol too complicated.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1992, **Simple Network Time Protocol** (**SNTP**) was defined to fill this niche.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The SNTPv3 standard describes a way to use NTPv3 such that no storage of state over an extended period is needed.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The topology becomes essentially the same as with the Time Protocol, as only one server is used.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 1996, SNTP was updated to SNTPv4, with some features of the then-in-development NTPv4.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] SNTPv4 was merged into the main NTPv4 standard in 2010.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] SNTP is fully interoperable with NTP since it does not define a new protocol, as it utilizes the same packet format and port as NTP, ensuring compatibility with NTP servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] However, client/server will lack the complex algorithms required to filter network jitter, analyze clock drift, or cross-reference multiple time sources.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] This makes it suitable for IoT devices and basic hardware that require "good enough" time without the overhead of a full NTP application stack.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] An SNTP client typically operates by querying a single server and applying the received time directly to the local clock.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] However, the simple algorithms provide times of reduced accuracy and thus it is inadvisable to sync time from an SNTP source.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] However, RFC 5905 notes that because the additional complexity of the full on-wire protocol is minimal, full implementation is encouraged even for simple clients.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP uses a hierarchical, semi-layered system of time sources.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Each level of this hierarchy is termed a *stratum* and is assigned a number starting with zero for the reference clock at the top.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A server synchronized to a stratum *n* server runs at stratum *n* + 1.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The number represents the distance from the reference clock and is used to prevent cyclical dependencies in the hierarchy.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Stratum is not always an indication of quality or reliability; it is common to find stratum 3 time sources that are higher quality than some stratum 2 time sources.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Brief descriptions of strata 0, 1, 2 and 3 are provided below.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP servers cannot advertise themselves as stratum 0; a stratum field set to 0 in an NTP message indicates an unspecified stratum.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] is synchronized to within a few microseconds of their attached stratum 0 devices.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] They are also referred to as primary time servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] These are computers that are synchronized over a network to stratum 1 servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Often a stratum 2 computer queries several stratum 1 servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Stratum 2 computers may also peer with other stratum 2 computers to provide more stable and robust time for all devices in the peer group.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] These are computers that are synchronized to stratum 2 servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] They employ the same algorithms for peering and data sampling as stratum 2, and can themselves act as servers for stratum 4 computers, and so on.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The upper limit for stratum is 15; stratum 16 is used to indicate that a device is unsynchronized.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The NTP algorithms on each computer interact to construct a Bellman–Ford shortest-path spanning tree, to minimize the accumulated round-trip delay to the stratum 1 servers for all the clients.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In addition to stratum, the protocol is able to identify the synchronization source for each server in terms of a reference identifier (refid).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] For servers on stratum 2 and below, the refid is an encoded form of the upstream time server's IP address.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] For IPv4, this is simply the 32-bit address; for IPv6, it would be the first 32 bits of the MD5 hash of the source address.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Refids serve to detect and prevent timing loops to the first degree.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The refid field is filled with status words in the case of kiss-o'-death (KoD) packets, which tell the client to stop sending requests so that the server can rest.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Some examples are INIT (initialization), STEP (step time change), and RATE (client requesting too fast).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The program output may additionally use codes not transmitted in the packet to indicate error, such as XFAC to indicate a network disconnection.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The IANA maintains a registry for refid source names and KoD codes.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The NTP reference implementation, along with the protocol, has been continuously developed for over 20 years.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Backwards compatibility has been maintained as new features have been added.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It contains several sensitive algorithms, especially to discipline the clock, that can misbehave when synchronized to servers that use different algorithms.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The software has been ported to almost every computing platform, including personal computers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It runs as a daemon called ntpd under Unix or as a service under Windows.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Reference clocks are supported and their offsets are filtered and analysed in the same way as remote servers, although they are usually polled more frequently.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] This implementation was audited in 2017, finding 14 potential security issues.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] All Microsoft Windows versions since Windows 2000 include the Windows Time service (W32Time), which has the ability to synchronize the computer clock to an NTP server.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] W32Time was originally implemented for the purpose of the Kerberos version 5 authentication protocol, which required time to be within 5 minutes of the correct value to prevent replay attacks.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The network time server in Windows 2000 Server (and Windows XP) does not implement NTP disciplined synchronization, only locally disciplined synchronization with NTP/SNTP correction.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Beginning with Windows Server 2003 and Windows Vista, the NTP provider for W32Time became compatible with a significant subset of NTPv3.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Microsoft states that W32Time cannot reliably maintain time synchronization with one second accuracy.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] If higher accuracy is desired, Microsoft recommends using a newer version of Windows or different NTP implementation.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Beginning with Windows 10 version 1607 and Windows Server 2016, W32Time can be configured to reach time accuracy of 1 s, 50 ms or 1 ms under certain specified operating conditions.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] In 2004, Henning Brauer of OpenBSD presented OpenNTPD, an NTPv3/SNTPv4 implementation with a focus on security and encompassing a privilege separated design.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Whilst it is aimed more closely at the simpler generic needs of OpenBSD users, it also includes some protocol security improvements while still being compatible with existing NTP servers.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The simpler code base sacrifices accuracy, deemed unnecessary in this use case.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A portable version is available in Linux package repositories.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTPsec is a fork of the reference implementation that has been systematically security-hardened.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The fork point was in June 2015 and was in response to a series of compromises in 2014.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The first production release shipped in October 2017.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Between removal of unsafe features, removal of support for obsolete hardware, and removal of support for obsolete Unix variants, NTPsec has been able to pare away 75% of the original codebase, making the remainder easier to audit.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A 2017 audit of the code showed eight security issues, including two that were not present in the original reference implementation, but NTPsec did not suffer from eight other issues that remained in the reference implementation.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] chrony is an independent NTP implementation mainly sponsored by Red Hat, who uses it as the default time program in their distributions.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Being written from scratch, chrony has a simpler codebase allowing for better security and lower resource consumption.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It does not however compromise on accuracy, instead syncing faster and better than the reference ntpd in many circumstances.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It is versatile enough for ordinary computers, which are unstable, go into sleep mode or have intermittent connection to the Internet.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It is also designed for virtual machines, a more unstable environment.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] chrony has been evaluated as "trustworthy", with only a few incidents.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It is able to achieve improved precision on LAN connections, using hardware timestamping on the network adapter.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Support for Network Time Security (NTS) was added on version 4.0. chrony is available under GNU General Public License version 2, was created by Richard Curnow in 1997 and is currently maintained by Miroslav Lichvar.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Support for NTS is available. ntpd-rs is part of the "Pendulum" project which also includes a Precision Time Protocol implementation "statime".
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Both projects are available under Apache and MIT software licenses.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] On the day of a leap second event, ntpd receives notification from either a configuration file, an attached reference clock, or a remote server.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Although the NTP clock is actually halted during the event, because of the requirement that time must appear to be strictly increasing, any processes that query the system time cause it to increase by a tiny amount, preserving the order of events.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] If a negative leap second should ever become necessary, it would be deleted with the sequence 23:59:58, 00:00:00, skipping 23:59:59.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] An alternative implementation, called leap smearing, consists in introducing the leap second incrementally during a period of 24 hours, from noon to noon in UTC time.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Because adjusting system time is generally a privileged operation, part or all of NTP code has to be run with some privileges in order to support its core functionality.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Only a few other security problems have been identified in the reference implementation of the NTP codebase, but those that appeared in 2009, such as arbitrary code execution and denial-of-service attacks, were cause for significant concern.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The protocol has been undergoing revision and review throughout its history.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The codebase for the reference implementation has undergone security audits from several sources for several years.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A stack buffer overflow exploit was discovered and patched in 2014.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Apple was concerned enough about this vulnerability that it used its auto-update capability for the first time.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] On systems using the reference implementation, which is running with root user's credential, this could allow unlimited access.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Some other implementations, such as OpenNTPD, have smaller code base and adopted other mitigation measures like privilege separation, are not subject to this flaw.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A 2017 security audit of three NTP implementations, conducted on behalf of the Linux Foundation's Core Infrastructure Initiative, suggested that both NTP and NTPsec were more problematic than chrony from a security standpoint.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP servers can be susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks unless packets are cryptographically signed for authentication.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The computational overhead involved can make this impractical on busy servers, particularly during denial of service attacks.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP message spoofing from a man-in-the-middle attack can be used to alter clocks on client computers and allow a number of attacks based on bypassing of cryptographic key expiration.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Some of the services affected by fake NTP messages identified are TLS, DNSSEC, various caching schemes (such as DNS cache), Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), Bitcoin and a number of persistent login schemes.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP has been used in distributed denial of service attacks.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] A small query is sent to an NTP server with the return IP address spoofed to be the target address.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Similar to the DNS amplification attack, the server responds with a much larger reply that allows an attacker to substantially increase the amount of data being sent to the target.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] To avoid participating in an attack, NTP server software can be upgraded or servers can be configured to ignore external queries.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP itself includes support for authenticating servers to clients.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTPv3 supports a symmetric key mode, which is not useful against MITM.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The public key system known as "autokey" in NTPv4 adapted from IPSec offers useful authentication, but is not practical for a busy server.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Autokey was also later found to suffer from several design flaws, with no correction published, save for a change in the message authentication code.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Microsoft also has an approach to authenticate NTPv3/SNTPv4 packets using a Windows domain identity, known as MS-SNTP.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] This system is implemented in the reference ntpd and chrony, using samba for the domain connection.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Indicates the distance from the reference clock.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Maximum interval between successive messages, in log₂(seconds).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Signed log₂(seconds) of system clock precision (e.g., –18 ≈ 1 microsecond).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Total round-trip delay to the reference clock, in NTP short format.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Total dispersion to the reference clock, in NTP short format.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Identifies the specific server or reference clock; interpretation depends on Stratum.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Time when the system clock was last set or corrected, in NTP timestamp format.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Time at the client when the request departed, in NTP timestamp format.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The local time, in timestamp format, when the latest NTP message arrived.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Time at the server when the response left, in NTP timestamp format.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Unsigned integer designating an MD5 key shared by the client and server.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] MD5 hash covering the packet header and extension fields, used for authentication.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The 64-bit binary fixed-point timestamps used by NTP consist of a 32-bit part for seconds and a 32-bit part for fractional second, giving a time scale that rolls over every 232 seconds (136 years) and a theoretical resolution of 2−32 seconds (233 picoseconds).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Therefore, the first rollover occurs on February 7, 2036.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTPv4 introduces a 128-bit date format: 64 bits for the second and 64 bits for the fractional-second.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] However, the 128-bit format is never transmitted as the standard states that eras "cannot be produced by NTP directly, nor is there need to do so." The most-significant 32 bits of this format is the *Era Number* which would resolve rollover ambiguity in most cases.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] According to Mills, "The 64-bit value for the fraction is enough to resolve the amount of time it takes a photon to pass an electron at the speed of light.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] DHCPv4 allows clients to automatically obtain time sources as part of initial network configuration.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] It is commonly used in managed networks to ensure dynamic time synchronisation without manual configuration.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] RFC 2132 defines a dedicated DHCPv4 option for distributing NTP server addresses to clients.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The *Network Time Protocol Servers* option carries a list of IPv4 addresses identifying NTP servers available to the client.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Servers should be listed in order of preference, allowing the client to select the most appropriate source.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] While the Network Time Protocol (NTP) is responsible for synchronising system clocks to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), it does not distribute local time zone information.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Time zone configuration is handled separately at the operating system level.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] This is especially useful for networks where devices are moving in and out, like cellular network.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Reduce the need to defined directly on device.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] These options are defined in RFC 4833 and apply to both DHCP for IPv4 (DHCPv4) and IPv6 (DHCPv6).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] Both options contain a variable-length string and are not null-terminated.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] This option carries a time zone definition using the POSIX `TZ` environment variable format (as specified in IEEE 1003.1), except that the string must not begin with a colon (`:`).
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] For this option to be useful, the client must already have a local copy of the time zone database.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] If the client recognizes the provided name, it should prefer this option over the POSIX string.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] If the name is unknown, the option must be ignored.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] The semantics and string formats are identical to those used in DHCPv4; only the binary encoding differs due to protocol differences between DHCPv4 and DHCPv6.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] NTP distributes only absolute time (UTC) and does not include any information about local time zones or daylight saving rules.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] DHCP time zone options complement NTP by allowing clients to automatically configure their local time representation after their clocks have been synchronised.
[src:ntp-protocol/network-time-protocol] This separation keeps NTP simple and avoids embedding region-specific political and legal time rules into the time synchronisation protocol.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The **Precision Time Protocol** (**PTP**) is a protocol for clock synchronization throughout a computer network with relatively high precision as compared to using the earlier developed Network Time Protocol (NTP) and therefore *potentially* higher accuracy depending on the configuration.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] In a local area network (LAN), accuracy can be sub-microsecond – making it suitable for measurement and control systems applications.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2008**, also known as PTP Version 2, is not backward compatible with the 2002 version.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2019** was published in November 2019 and includes backward-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 includes a *profile* concept defining PTP operating parameters and options.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Several profiles have been defined for applications including telecommunications, electric power distribution and audiovisual uses.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 802.1AS** is an adaptation of PTP, called gPTP, for use with Audio Video Bridging (AVB) and Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN).
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] According to John Eidson, who led the IEEE 1588-2002 standardization effort, "IEEE 1588 is designed to fill a niche not well served by either of the two dominant protocols, NTP and GPS.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588 is designed for local systems requiring accuracies beyond those attainable using NTP.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] PTP was originally defined in the IEEE 1588-2002 standard, officially titled *Standard for a Precision Clock Synchronization Protocol for Networked Measurement and Control Systems*, and published in 2002.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] In 2008, IEEE 1588-2008 was released as a revised standard; also known as PTP version 2 (PTPv2), it improves accuracy, precision and robustness but is not backward compatible with the original 2002 version.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2019 was published in November 2019, is informally known as *PTPv2.1* and includes backwards-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The IEEE 1588 standards describe a hierarchical master–slave architecture for clock distribution consisting of one or more network segments and one or more clocks.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] An *ordinary clock* is a device with a single network connection that is either the source of or the destination for a synchronization reference.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A source is called a *master* (alternately *timeTransmitter*), and a destination is called a *slave* (alternately *timeReceiver*).
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A *boundary clock* has multiple network connections and synchronizes one network segment to another.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A single, synchronization leader is selected, a.k.a. elected, for each network segment.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The root timing reference is called the *grandmaster*.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A relatively simple PTP architecture consists of ordinary clocks on a single-segment network with no boundary clocks.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A grandmaster is elected and all other clocks synchronize to it.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 introduces a clock associated with network equipment used to convey PTP messages.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The *transparent clock* modifies PTP messages as they pass through the device.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Timestamps in the messages are corrected for time spent traversing the network equipment.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] This scheme improves distribution accuracy by compensating for delivery variability across the network.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] PTP typically uses the same epoch as Unix time (start of 1 January 1970).
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] While the Unix time is based on Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and is subject to leap seconds, PTP is based on International Atomic Time (TAI).
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The PTP grandmaster communicates the current offset between UTC and TAI, so that UTC can be computed from the received PTP time.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Synchronization and management of a PTP system is achieved through the exchange of messages across the communications medium.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] To this end, PTP uses the following message types.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Messages are categorized as *event* and *general* messages.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] *Event* messages are time-critical in that accuracy in transmission and receipt timestamp accuracy directly affects clock distribution accuracy.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] *Sync*, *Delay_Req*, *Pdelay_Req* and *Pdelay_resp* are *event* messages.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages are more conventional protocol data units in that the data in these messages is of importance to PTP, but their transmission and receipt timestamps are not.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] *Announce*, *Follow_Up*, *Delay_Resp*, *Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up*, *Management* and *Signaling* messages are members of the *general* message class.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] PTP messages may use the User Datagram Protocol over Internet Protocol (UDP/IP) for transport.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses only IPv4 transports, but this has been extended to include IPv6 in IEEE 1588-2008.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2002, all PTP messages are sent using multicast messaging, while IEEE 1588-2008 introduced an option for devices to negotiate unicast transmission on a port-by-port basis.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Multicast transmissions use IP multicast addressing, for which multicast group addresses are defined for IPv4 and IPv6 (see table).
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Time-critical *event* messages (Sync, Delay_req, Pdelay_Req and Pdelay_Resp) are sent to port number 319.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages (Announce, Follow_Up, Delay_Resp, Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up, management and signaling) use port number 320.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2008, encapsulation is also defined for DeviceNet, ControlNet and PROFINET.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A domain is an interacting set of clocks that synchronize to one another using PTP.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Clocks are assigned to a domain by virtue of the contents of the *Subdomain name* (IEEE 1588-2002) or the *domainNumber* (IEEE 1588-2008) fields in PTP messages they receive or generate.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Domains allow multiple clock distribution systems to share the same communications medium.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Class – each clock is a member of a given class, each class getting its own priority.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Priority 2 – final-defined priority, defining backup order in case the other criteria were not sufficient.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Smaller numeric values indicate higher priority.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Unique identifier – MAC address-based selection is used as a tiebreaker when all other properties are equal.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses a selection algorithm based on similar properties.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Clock properties are advertised in IEEE 1588-2002 *Sync* messages and in IEEE 1588-2008 *Announce* messages.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The current leader transmits this information at regular interval.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A clock that considers itself a better leader will transmit this information in order to invoke a change of leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Once the current leader recognizes the better clock, the current leader stops transmitting *Sync* messages and associated clock properties (*Announce* messages in the case of IEEE 1588-2008) and the better clock takes over as leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The BMCA only considers the self-declared quality of clocks and does not take network link quality into consideration.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Via BMCA, PTP selects a source of time for an IEEE 1588 domain and for each network segment in the domain.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Clocks determine the offset between themselves and their leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Let the variable t represent physical time.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] where $s(t)$ represents the time measured by the follower clock at physical time t , and $m(t)$ represents the time measured by the leader clock at physical time t .
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The leader periodically broadcasts the current time as a message to the other clocks.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2002 broadcasts are up to once per second.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2008, up to 10 per second are permitted.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Each broadcast begins at time $T_{1}$ with a *Sync* message sent by the leader to all the clocks in the domain.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] A clock receiving this message takes note of the local time $T_{1}'$ when this message is received.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The leader may subsequently send a multicast *Follow_Up* with accurate $T_{1}$ timestamp.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Not all leaders have the ability to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] It is only after the transmission is complete that they are able to retrieve an accurate timestamp for the *Sync* transmission from their network hardware.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with this limitation use the *Follow_Up* message to convey $T_{1}$ .
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with PTP capabilities built into their network hardware are able to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message and do not need to send Follow_Up messages.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] In order to accurately synchronize to their leader, clocks must individually determine the network transit time of the *Sync* messages.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The transit time is determined indirectly by measuring round-trip time from each clock to its leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The clocks initiate an exchange with their leader designed to measure the transit time d .
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The exchange begins with a clock sending a *Delay_Req* message at time $T_{2}$ to the leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The leader receives and timestamps the *Delay_Req* at time $T_{2}'$ and responds with a *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The leader includes the timestamp $T_{2}'$ in the *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The clock now knows the offset ${\tilde {o}}$ during this transaction and can correct itself by this amount to bring it into agreement with their leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] One assumption is that this exchange of messages happens over a period of time so small that this offset can safely be considered constant over that period.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Another assumption is that the transit time of a message going from the leader to a follower is equal to the transit time of a message going from the follower to the leader.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] Finally, it is assumed that both the leader and follower can accurately measure the time they send or receive a message.
[src:ntp-protocol/precision-time-protocol] The degree to which these assumptions hold true determines the accuracy of the clock at the follower device.
